DO  - 10.2307/2298104
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 60
IS  - 4
SP  - 889
EP  - 902
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper investigates the response of the price level to random monetary shocks through a model of the fixed cost of changing a nominal price. It shows that in an inflationary environment, an expansionary monetary shock is accommodated faster than a contractionary monetary shock. Furthermore, when the average rate of monetary expansion increases, the lag in response to a positive shock decreases. The study also proves that the relationship between the expected rate of inflation and the variance of real prices is positive only above a critical level of expected inflation.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2298104
ER  - 



